Class TestContext

  • java.lang.Object
    • java.util.Dictionary<K,V>
      • java.util.Hashtable<java.lang.Object,java.lang.Object>
        • java.util.Properties
          • bench.TestContext
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    java.io.Serializable, java.lang.Cloneable, java.util.Map<java.lang.Object,java.lang.Object>

    public class TestContext
extends java.util.Properties
    Extends Properties to parse and manage runtime parameters for test programs. The TestParams class provides greater control over the input parameters that characterize a test. While the actual name value pairs for parameters are always stored as Strings in the parent Properties object, TestParams adds additional management and validation. For example, it provides a mechanism for statically declaring known parameters, along with descriptive information, default values and some primitive type information. The application can retrieve parameter values as simple properties, using the Properties.getProperty(String) method, or can use accessor functions (getInt, getBool, getString) to cast return values to a specific Java type. The embedded TestParam class is a wrapper holding this metadata for a particular parameter type.

    Parameters can be entered and parsed in a variety of ways:

    1. Default values (defined in TestParam static initializer)
    2. Command line argument array (type String[])
    3. System properties.
    4. Properties file (default filename params.properties)
    5. Explicit reset of property via TestParams.set method)
    6. Interactive prompt (if -prompt specified in cmd line args

    To add a new parameter type at runtime, you simply include it on the command line as a name/value pair, e.g.: 


    java com.parelastic.bench.Driver -props in.prop myParam=4,otherParam=England
    Programatically, you add new parameters by invoking one of the static TestParam.add methods. Note that the way parameters are displayed in printouts and prompts will correspond to the sequence in which they are created, and these displays will be broken into categories based on the category string names entered via the TestParam.addCategory method. All the built-in parameters are added via a static initializer in this class using those methods.

    The validate() method performs some specific validation checks on parameter values, based on data type and other constraints passed in when you added the param.

      • TestContext

        public TestContext()
        Set up hashmap with initial values for all params. Note that the static TestParam collections are already built. This constructor goes through the standard driver params in the list and sets the default value. If a system property of the same name exists, it overrides the compile-time default.

    • Method Detail

      • getInt

        public int getInt(java.lang.String propName)
        Return a parameter as an int.

        If the final character of the string is 'k', 'm' or 'g', it indicates that the scale is in kilo-, mega-, or giga- units (i.e. 1024,1024*1024 or 1024*1024*1024).

        If the current value of the input property is not a valid integer, this routine will attempt to find a default value for that property in the standard list of params. If that doesn't work it simply returns '1'.`

        Parameters:
        propName - Lookup key for a property that represents an integer.`

      • getBool

        public boolean getBool(java.lang.String propName)

      • getString

        public java.lang.String getString(java.lang.String propName)
        Return a parameter as a non-null String. Take the Property string value, trim off leading and trailing whitespace, and convert null values to empty strings.

      • getEnumIndex

        public int getEnumIndex(java.lang.String propName)
        Return the enumeration index of the param as an int.

        The param type must be "enum" or an exception is raised. For enum types, a String array of the matching values is maintained and this routine simply returns the index within that array, or -1 if the value is not found.

        NOTE: Unlike param names, enum values are case-sensitive, so a warning message is printed if the match would have occurred on a case-insensitive search.

        Parameters:
        propName - Lookup key for a property that represents an enum.
        Returns:
        Index value if string found in enum validation list, -1 otherwise.

      • getIntValue

        public static int getIntValue(java.lang.String input)
        Uniform method for extracting int values from 'number' type parameters. This utility method allows you to specify values in whole numbers, kilobytes, megabytes or gigabytes (similar to the -Xms arg in the java cmd). If it cannot expand the string, it rethrows the NumberFormatException to the caller.
